 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'VincentTam', 'comment_id': 422691004.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-19 07:34:58+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_12', 'text': "If this issue is urgent, why don't consider [setting up your own API instance](https://www.flyinggrizzly.net/2017/12/setting-up-staticman-server/)?  Provided you have a (free) Heroku account, [the whole setup](https://vincenttam.gitlab.io/post/2018-09-16-staticman-powered-gitlab-pages/2/) can be done under fifteen&nbsp;minutes.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'maxime-michel', 'comment_id': 422693342.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-19 07:41:58+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_13', 'text': "Indeed, this is also the described solution in https://github.com/username_10/staticman/issues/222.

However, it is not explicitely described anywhere yet, and reduces the appeal quite a bit. As far as I'm concerned, I would rather pay a small fee than deploy my own.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'VincentTam', 'comment_id': 422700807.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-19 08:06:16+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_12', 'text': "As a consequence of [@username_10's request](https://github.com/username_10/staticman/pull/219#issuecomment-417657297), I've really built [one running on a free Heroku dyno](https://staticman3.herokuapp.com) to test the newly available #219 GitLab suuport.  The associated Git* bots are both named @staticmanlab.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'maxime-michel', 'comment_id': 422703828.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-19 08:16:30+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_13', 'text': "(Sorry, I wasn't talking about the deployment process, for which you've given an excellent and totally clear link, I was talking about the Staticman getting started: it doesn't mention these potential API limit problems yet.)", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'VincentTam', 'comment_id': 422709077.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-19 08:32:57+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_12', 'text': "@username_13 I see your point.  It's better to mention this limitation at the very beginning, so that users can choose between

1. use public API instance
2. setup own API instance

This is more efficient as @staticmanapp will receive less invitations.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'saifulmuhajir', 'comment_id': 424470977.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-25 19:28:12+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_14', 'text': "This still happened to me after waiting for five days. The response is still 'invitation not found'. Is there any workaround for this?

Thanks", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'VincentTam', 'comment_id': 424495509.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-25 20:46:17+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_12', 'text': "@username_14 As depicted on Staticman's set, Staticman functions basically like a :truck: truck which POSTs HTML :page_facing_up: form data into your GitHub/GitLab repo :file_folder: (running on any GitHub/GitLab server).

When a bus is not working, passengers would be asked to take another one.  Similarly, for a _workaround_, you can use [_my API instance_](https://staticman3.herokuapp.com) (built at the request of @username_10 for testing #219) or even [build your own instance](https://www.flyinggrizzly.net/2017/12/setting-up-staticman-server/) within Heroku's free tier.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'VincentTam', 'comment_id': 424598171.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-26 06:19:12+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_12', 'text': "@username_14 To bypass this invitation problem, why not try GitLab Pages?  In GitLab, there's no such invitation mechanism---you just add the bot (say @staticmanlab) into the contributing members.
 
If you really love open source, migrating from the _proprietary_ GitHub to _open souce_ GitLab, which has _native_ CD/CI support, will free you from the aforementioned GitHub API limit.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'VincentTam', 'comment_id': 424601901.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-26 06:37:12+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_12', 'text': '@username_2 I don't know about that, but a quick search points me to a GitLab forum question "*
Does GitLab have an API rate limit*".  The last comment lists out several endpoints which controls the traffic.  Hope that helps.

The last question is precisely the problem.  Now the :truck: is overloaded.  One may either wait (for an indefinite time period) for a larger truck, or build his/her own one.  Building the former costs surely a fortune, while building the later for a personal blog can be free.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'maxime-michel', 'comment_id': 424604350.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-26 06:48:21+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_13', 'text': "It would be nice to have a breakdown of the usage. Does somebody really believe that there's enough Staticman-powered websites for the bot to hit 5k requests an hour? I have a feeling that if anything, it is a spam problem that we have.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'Kulbhushan-Chand', 'comment_id': 424606252.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-26 06:56:28+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': "@username_12 Furthur exploring the link in the last comment that you mentioned, points thay GitLab indeed have api request limit
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17742733/46062276-e8c80080-c186-11e8-8633-e47fd728dca9.png)

Also mentioned [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/38478806/does-gitlab-api-have-a-rate-limit)

**Which means it is a matter of time when enough people use someone's GitLab api and hit 600 req/min.**

Looks like self hosted instance for your personal use only is the safe option, **BUT** that too only upto the limit that the number of users commenting on your self hosted staticman api should not collectively generates more than 600 req/min.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'saifulmuhajir', 'comment_id': 424696871.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-26 12:29:12+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_14', 'text': "This is a matter of scalability indeed.

Maybe we'll end up building federated commenting (API) system where people can build their API servers (with their request limits) and join them with existing ones.

Also, if @username_2 picture says 600 req/min/IP that's actually good enough for normal people because one IP should have less than 600 requests per minute.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'Kulbhushan-Chand', 'comment_id': 424949691.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-27 03:49:59+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': 'but only if they have deployed their own personal api instance. If group of staticman users ends up using the same api, the limit will be easily achieved.

As mentioned by @username_12 [here ](https://github.com/username_10/staticman/issues/227#issuecomment-424495509) about the steps of deployment, it is still not easy for majority of people.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'maxime-michel', 'comment_id': 424957445.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-27 04:44:05+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_13', 'text': "Wait, what? Let's say 50 people use the same deployment. 600 req/min / 50 sites = 12 requests per minute per site. That means at the end of the week, each site would have received a maximum of 12\*60\*24\*7 = 120k comments.

The same math applied to GitHub means 50 sites each get a maximum of 16k comments per week.

On my most visited website (800-1000 daily visits), I get maximum 10 comments a week. I have Staticman running on 3 sites so in the end even that 'high figure' gets drowned into a very low average of 3. Am I missing something or is some spammer abusing the tool?", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'Kulbhushan-Chand', 'comment_id': 424970178.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-27 06:09:01+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': "üëç Thanks for the math part. Honestly I didn't calculate the numbers when commenting.

Even 12 request per minute per site can be a bottleneck at the peak time of the site visit (only for some very interesting article/site). (Please note I don't have any research fact)

With the growing popularity of staticman, there can be more than 50 people using some specific api instance (this is what happening now with @staticmanapp on github). 

I am sure with the use of reCaptcha with staticman, spamming is negligible.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'maxime-michel', 'comment_id': 424980509.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-27 07:01:02+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_13', 'text': "50 was just an example to show we have an extremely large comments per minute / site ratio at our disposal. Yet people have been consistently unable to add Staticman as a collaborator for a month. In my opinion, either we have too many unmaintained sites that weren't set up with captchas and get spam, or somebody is deliberately bricking the instance.", 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'Kulbhushan-Chand', 'comment_id': 425157977.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-27 16:29:41+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': 'If someone deliberately bricking it, the best way is -- hitting the api from different IPs concurrently to reach the limit per minute using `https://api.staticman.net/v2/entry/{GITHUB USERNAME}/{GITHUB REPOSITORY}}`

In any-case we need data/log (if available) of @staticmanapp to find out the cause.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'maxime-michel', 'comment_id': 425634570.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-29 10:28:35+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_13', 'text': 'Excellent catch, @username_12. I vote for adding a captcha or an Akismet key to that site.', 'title': None, 'type': 'comment'}
 {'action': 'created', 'author': 'Kulbhushan-Chand', 'comment_id': 425643163.0, 'datetime': '2018-09-29 12:55:38+00:00', 'masked_author': 'username_2', 'text': '@username_12  Allow me to correct, by commits if you mean pull requests. Since there are only 30 commits out of which only few are caused by staticman comment entry.

